[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test improvements**\n\nI'm thinking about how to avoid hardcoding artifact versions in assertions. It might be better for a test to fail if JDK<24 isn't installed, instead of silently passing, since coverage is important. Under JDK21, if `securityManagerInstalled` is false due to unsupported conditions, it passes, hiding coverage issues. I could assert on supported Java versions, though JDK24 isn't possible. I need to find a way to detect JDK <24 without skipping tests in native images.\n\n**Examining security manager tests**\n\nI'm considering better coverage for CI with JDK21 and the jvmArg class name. I might need to assert if the previous security manager matches our startup type. There's also a thought about removing the \"allow\" property. If a custom startup security manager is installed, would any test check if `System.getSecurityManager() == null`? It seems that ByteBuddy source tests aren't covering that. I'm also pondering a rule against using `$` in test class or file names, though our build.gradle includes it. It might be an issue for some reviewers.\n\n**Exploring security manager options**\n\nI’m thinking about using `java.security.manager=default` with a policy granting all permissions dynamically generated in build.gradle, but there might be too much complexity if I write a file under build. A custom security manager string seems like a better option. Also, I need to keep in mind that I shouldn’t run certain tests. Before finalizing my approach, it might be helpful to show a diff for the relevant files to clarify changes.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_05c9d7b3619b2e0b0169fc96e3d544819e9c8acdf9f6686ce9\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_JbyzoMICtuafTfKDmDWviVHtbVtaxspx7B342P9lBfJMibcT1YNGX_MbXZ6KoiFRySRCmhlcMpMUqa266sTlQGo1WuSvjC6YbtsI_J5kzyLOC0OgDr7pT1t-6B2ghdQhtv4DEk0-GxhLaL4RTT5-if2q_KJf5BPfwx5Bb1-0